      <title>Test Doubles in JUnit</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/ii-gui/13-test-doubles/07-junit-test-doubles/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc410/ii-gui/13-test-doubles/07-junit-test-doubles/</guid>
      <description>YouTube Video
Video Materials
To create test doubles in JUnit, we&amp;rsquo;ll rely on a separate library called Mockito. Mockito is a framework for creating mock objects in Java that works well with JUnit, and has become one of the most commonly used tools for this task.
Installing Mockito in Gradle To install Mockito, we just update the testImplementation line in our build.gradle file to include both the mockito-inline library, as well as the mockito-junit-jupiter library that allows Mockito and JUnit to work together seamlessly.</description>
